{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":6987,"record_hash":"sha256:03f0a41fa93765133e90ace45ddd9dd2a339d695d559999f946ba1e0cecc05ff","timestamp":"2026-05-07T19:27:44.046Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. The antidote is mostly to make the code look authored rather than generated: fewer generic shapes, more local judgment, and tests/docs that encode why the shape exists.\n\nI researched a few useful sources:\n- Google’s code review guide emphasizes design fit, complexity, tests, naming, comments, docs, and reviewing every line in context, with special suspicion for over-engineering.\n  [Google Engineering Practices](https://google.github.io/eng-practices/review/reviewer/looking-for.html)\n- Rust API Guidelines give us a concrete crate-review checklist: naming, meaningful errors, private fields, type safety, predictability, docs, Debug, etc.\n  [Rust API Guidelines](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/checklist.html)\n- GitHub’s AI-generated-code review guide calls out context/intent verification, dependency scrutiny, hallucinated APIs, skipped tests, and human standards for maintainability.\n  [GitHub Docs](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/tutorials/review-ai-generated-code)\n- Fowler’s “code smells” framing is useful here: smells are quick indicators, not automatic crimes. For our case, “speculative generality” is especially relevant.\n  [Fowler on Code Smells](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CodeSmell.html), [Speculative Generality](https://refactoring.guru/smells/speculative-generality)\n- Anthropic’s Claude Code guide recommends explore → plan → implement, specific context, and giving the agent verification criteria.\n  [Claude Code Best Practices](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)\n- Simon Willison’s agentic engineering note makes a blunt but good point: first run the tests; code that has never been executed is luck.\n  [First run the tests](https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/first-run-the-tests/)\n\nFor `but-agentlog`, I’d run a focused “de-AI” hardening pass like this:\n\n1. **Deletion Pass**\n   Look for fake extensibility: one-use helpers, generic names, abstraction for hypothetical agents, unnecessary structs, option fields that are always present, comments that narrate the obvious.\n\n2. **Domain Naming Pass**\n   Rename generic concepts to the exact thing they are in this POC. Good names should explain the capture workflow without a paragraph.\n\n3. **Boundary Pass**\n   Confirm the shape is still:\n   `cli -> capture -> transcript parser -> gitmeta writer -> redaction`\n   No repo rediscovery in business logic, no CLI concerns leaking into parser/writer, no GitMeta details leaking into transcript parsing.\n\n4. **Rust API Pass**\n   Keep almost everything `pub(crate)` or private. Check `Debug`, error clarity, owned vs borrowed values, unnecessary clones, and whether typed errors stop at the library boundary while `anyhow` stays in CLI glue.\n\n5. **Test Intent Pass**\n   Tests should describe behavior, not implementation trivia. Especially: partial final lines, dedupe, dry-run no writes, redaction, cwd validation, Claude/Codex field extraction. If a test would pass after a broken rewrite, sharpen it.\n\n6. **Module Shape Pass**\n   `gitmeta.rs` is probably the one to inspect most carefully because it owns both read-only dry-run SQL and write behavior. We should improve it only where real comprehension improves, not split it just to split it.\n\n7. **AI-Specific Review Pass**\n   Ask fresh reviewers to look only for:\n   “Does this look generated?”\n   “What would a maintainer misunderstand in 6 months?”\n   “What is too generic for a two-agent POC?”\n   “Which tests are asserting the shape instead of the behavior?”\n\nMy suggested next move: do a no-behavior-change review/edit pass over `crates/but-agentlog`, starting with production code only, then tests. Keep each cleanup small and run the same validation after.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T19:27:44.046Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}